EXTRACTION RULES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

1. SCENE BOUNDARIES: each scene is a coherent causal unit — a location shift, a
   power-relation shift, or a revelation that changes what characters know or want.
   Do not split mechanically by time; split by narrative causality.

2. SCENE ID FORMAT: "ep{{ episode_id }}_sc_01", "ep{{ episode_id }}_sc_02", etc.
   Always zero-pad to two digits.

3. scene_start_time / scene_end_time: copy the SRT timestamp of the FIRST subtitle
   line of the scene into scene_start_time, and the END timestamp of the LAST
   subtitle line into scene_end_time.  Use the exact SRT format: HH:MM:SS,mmm
   (e.g. "00:03:12,480").  These are used for video clip extraction.

4. scene_actions: a list of concrete facts about what characters DO or DECIDE
   in this scene. State facts — do not evaluate or judge intensity.

5. unresolved_debt: the specific causal obligation, secret, or threat that this
   scene leaves hanging. One sentence, factual.  If nothing is left unresolved,
   write null.

6. pivot_signals: words, actions, or revelations in this scene that will
   structurally reverberate in later episodes. Be specific (e.g. "X learns that
   Y has the contract").  Empty list if none.

7. structured_dialogues: for lines that reveal character intent, hidden
   knowledge, or power shifts, capture them with the speaker name from the
   KNOWN CHARACTERS list above.  Assign "UNKNOWN" only when you truly cannot
   infer the speaker.  Omit trivial filler lines.

ABSOLUTE PROHIBITION:
  ✗ No percentages, numeric scores, or intensity ratings of any kind
  ✗ No phrases like "crisis saturation", "tension level", "dramatic weight"
  ✗ No subjective adjectives quantifying emotional states (e.g. "highly tense")
  ✗ Stick to observable, causal, factual statements only

